Eric Dishman is an Intel Fellow and general manager of Intel's Health Strategy & Solutions Group. He founded the product research and innovation team responsible for driving Intel’s worldwide healthcare research, new product innovation, strategic planning, and health policy and standards activities.

Dishman is recognized globally for driving healthcare reform through home and community-based technologies and services, with a focus on enabling independent living for seniors. His work has been featured in The New York Times, Washington Post and Businessweek, and The Wall Street Journal named him one of “12 People Who Are Changing Your Retirement.” He has delivered keynotes on independent living for events such as the annual Consumer Electronics Show, the IAHSA International Conference and the National Governors Association. He has published numerous articles on independent living technologies and co-authored government reports on health information technologies and health reform.

He has co-founded organizations devoted to advancing independent living, including the Technology Research for Independent Living Centre, the Center for Aging Services Technologies, the Everyday Technologies for Alzheimer’s Care program, and the Oregon Center for Aging & Technology.

title: Health care should be a team sport

aws-transcripts.transcript: I want to share some personal friends and stories with you that I've actually never talked about in public before to help illustrate the idea and the need and the hope for us to reinvent our health care system around the world. 24 years ago, I had a sophomore in college at a series of fainting spell. No alcohol was involved. Uh, and I ended up in student health and they ran some lab work and came back right away and said kidney problems. And before I knew it, I was involved and thrown into this sort of six months of tests and trials and tribulations with six doctors across to hospitals in this sort of clash of medical titans to figure out which one of them was right about what was wrong with me. And I'm sitting in a waiting room some time later for an ultrasound, and all six of these doctors actually show up in the room at once. And I'm like, Oh, this is bad news. And their diagnosis was this. Hey, said you have two rare kidney diseases that are gonna actually destroy your kidneys. Eventually, you have cancer like cells in your immune system that we need to start treatment right away and you'll never be eligible for a kidney transplant. And you're not likely to live more than two or three years now with the gravity of this doomsday diagnosis is just It just sucked me in immediately. And as if I began preparing myself as a patient to die, according to the schedule that they had just given to me until I met a patient named Virna in a waiting room who became a dear friend. And she grabbed me one day and took me off to the medical library and did a bunch of research on these diagnoses and these diseases and said, Eric, these people who get this are normally in their seventies and eighties. They don't know anything about you. Wake up, take control of your health and get on with your life. And I did you know these people making these proclamation Me. We're not bad people. In fact, these professionals were miracle workers, but they're working in a flawed, expensive system that's set up the wrong way. It's dependent on hospitals and clinics for our every care need. It's dependent on specialists who just look at parts of us. It's dependent on guesswork of diagnoses and drug cocktails. And still something either works or you die. And it's dependent on passive patients who just take it and don't ask any questions. Now the problem with this model is that it's unsustainable. Globally, it's unaffordable globally. We need to invent what I call a personal health system. So what does this personal health system look like? And what new technologies and rolls is it gonna entail? Now, I'm gonna start by actually sharing with you a new friend of mine, Libby. Somebody have become quite attached to over the last six months. This is Libby. Or actually, this is an ultrasound image of Libby. This is the kidney transplant I was never supposed to have. Now, this is an image that we shot a couple of weeks ago for today, and you'll notice on the edge of this image. There's some dark spots. There was just really concerning to me. So we're gonna actually do alive exam to sort of see how Libby's doing. This is not a wardrobe malfunction. I have to take my belt off here. Don't you in the front row worry or anything? um I'm gonna use a device from a company called Moby Sante. This is a portable ultrasound that can plug into a smartphone comm plug into a tablet mobile.
